        <section id="Aundha Nagnath Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Aundha Nagnath Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Aundha Nagnath Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>The Aundha Nagnath Temple, located in Hingoli district, Maharashtra, holds immense significance as one of the twelve sacred Jyotirlingas dedicated to Lord Shiva. This ancient shrine, considered the eighth Jyotirlinga, is revered for its historical roots, tracing back to the Mahabharata era with legends suggesting it was built by Yudhishthira, and its captivating blend of Hemadpanthi and Maratha architectural styles. The temple, sprawling over 60,000 square feet, is particularly notable for its distinct basement sanctum (Garbhagriha) where the Jyotirlinga is enshrined, accessed by a narrow flight of stairs. Adding to its intrigue is the placement of Nandi (Shiva's bull) at the rear of the temple, an unusual layout believed to be linked to a miraculous incident involving the saint Namdev, where the temple rotated in response to his devotion. This site is not only a Hindu pilgrimage center but also holds reverence for Sikhs due to its strong association with Sant Namdev, whose hymns are incorporated into the Guru Granth Sahib, and the belief that Guru Nanak also visited the shrine. The Aundha Nagnath temple stands as a testament to the rich architectural heritage of the Yadava dynasty, showcasing the Hemadpanthi style through its intricately carved black stone structure built using the dry masonry technique, though the upper portion and spire were likely rebuilt in the Maratha style during the renovation efforts spearheaded by Ahilyabai Holkar. Its status as a 'Protected Monument of National Importance' by the Archaeological Survey of India further underscores its historical and cultural value, drawing devotees seeking blessings and solace in its tranquil and spiritually charged atmosphere. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Mallinath Digambar Jain Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Mallinath Digambar Jain Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Mallinath Digambar Jain Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>The Mallinath Digambar Jain Temple, located in Shirad Shahapur village within Aundha Nagnath Taluka of Hingoli district, Maharashtra, is a significant pilgrimage site for the Jain community. This temple, which is around 300 years old, houses a revered statue of Lord Mallinath. According to legend, the idol was originally in Ardhapur, but Bhattarak Shree Premanand, dissatisfied with its location among other idols, sought permission from the Nizam to move it to Karanja. However, a dream during his travels instructed him to establish the idol in Shirad Shahapur, leading to the temple's construction at its current location. The temple is intricately carved with marble, featuring ancient stories depicted on its walls, and includes a 4-foot-high black stone idol of Lord Mallinath in the Ardha padmasana posture. Pilgrims from all over India visit this site, which also offers accommodation facilities. The temple is the only Atishaya Kshetra (place of miracles) in India dedicated to Lord Mallinath. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Tulja Bhavani Sansthan" class="section">
            <h2>Tulja Bhavani Sansthan</h2>
            <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcTIaK9hdF30fmu0ujdJa_VYtXjzFamPgR3M_tQoe-iYAeLH97VV8j-buLIQV1GhfnSKWcs&usqp=CAU" alt="Tulja Bhavani Sansthan" class="section-image">
            <p>In Parbhani, Maharashtra, there are several temples dedicated to the goddess Tulja Bhavani. These temples are revered by the local community and visited by devotees seeking the blessings of the deity. Some prominent temples include the Shri Tulaja Bhavani Mata Mandir in Trimurti Nagar, the Tulja Bhavani Devi Mandir and Navshya Maruti Mandir TulajaBhavani Mandir in Swapnapurti, Ramkrishna Nagar, and the Tulja Bhavani Mandir in Kumbhari. The Navshya Maruti Mandir TulajaBhavani Mandir, for example, maintains consistent opening hours from 7 AM to 9 PM daily. These temples serve as important centers of devotion and contribute to the rich religious and cultural landscape of the region. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Sant Namdev Sansthan" class="section">
            <h2>Sant Namdev Sansthan</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Sant Namdev Sansthan" class="section-image">
            <p>The Sant Namdev Sansthan, located in Narsi Namdev village, Hingoli district, Maharashtra, is a revered pilgrimage site marking the birthplace of the 13th-century saint and poet Namdev. Born in 1270, Namdev Damaji Relekar was a prominent figure in the Varkari tradition, known for his devotional songs (Abhangs), some of which are even included in the sacred scriptures of Sikhism, the Adi Granth. The Sansthan, which includes a temple dedicated to the saint, has been recognized by the Maharashtra government as a significant religious and tourist destination, attracting devotees and visitors alike. Annual fairs, like the one associated with the "Mitha Yatra" (Salt Journey) and the celebrations during Ashadhi Ekadashi, further enhance the Sansthan's spiritual and cultural significance. Sikh devotees, who hold Sant Namdev in high regard, are actively engaged in building a Gurudwara and a memorial for the saint at Narsi. The Sansthan thus stands as a testament to the life and teachings of Sant Namdev and continues to be a vibrant center of devotion and pilgrimage in Maharashtra. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Hingoli Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Hingoli Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Hingoli Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>This fort, while located in Hingoli district, is more accessible from Jintur in Parbhani district, situated about 60 km from Hingoli and 30 km from Jintur. The fort covers approximately 5 acres and features impressive stone ramparts about 25 feet high with four gates, one in each cardinal direction, and five bastions. Inside, steps lead up to the ramparts, enabling visitors to walk along them. The fort also includes a Dattatraya temple at its center, surrounded by the Samadhi temples of Navnath, and a Shiva temple with a Nandi statue. Overpasses and a subway are also part of the fort's structure. While the fort's specific history is not well-documented, local accounts suggest it was used as a camp by the Nizam's Razakar army during the Hyderabad independence struggle. Due to its elevated position, the fort provides scenic views of the surrounding villages and the Yedrai Dam reservoir. A visit to the fort typically takes around half an hour. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Dargah of Hazrat Sayyad Shah Fariduddin" class="section">
            <h2>Dargah of Hazrat Sayyad Shah Fariduddin</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Dargah of Hazrat Sayyad Shah Fariduddin" class="section-image">
            <p>The Dargah of Hazrat Sayyad Shah Fariduddin Parbhani is a significant shrine located on Dargah Road, Parbhani, Maharashtra, India. It is more widely known as Dargah Hazrat Sayed Shah Turaabul Haq (R.A) and is the final resting place of the great Sufi saint Hazrat Turabul Haq, who is also referred to as Turatpeer Baba. This dargah stands as a powerful symbol of unity among various religious communities, attracting thousands of devotees of all faiths who gather annually for the Urs (death anniversary) fair held between February 2nd and February 15th. People visit the dargah seeking blessings and often claim that their wishes are fulfilled after praying at the site, which has earned it the reputation as the "Ajmer Sharif of Maharashtra" due to its immense popularity. The shrine is accessible 24 hours a day and is well-connected by road and rail networks, with the nearest airports located in Aurangabad and Nanded. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Siddheshwar Dam" class="section">
            <h2>Siddheshwar Dam</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Siddheshwar Dam" class="section-image">
            <p>Siddheshwar Dam is an earth-fill dam constructed on the Purna River, a tributary of the Godavari River, in 1968. Located in the northwestern part of Aundha Nagnath in the Hingoli district of Maharashtra, India, it stands at a height of 38.26 meters (125.5 ft) and has a length of 6,353.2 meters (20,844 ft). The dam, also known as Rupur Camp, is owned by the Government of Maharashtra. Its primary functions are to provide irrigation for the Aundha Nagnath and Basmath tehsils of Hingoli and supply drinking water to nearby cities like Nanded and Basmath. The dam also holds the Siddheshwar reservoir, which has a total capacity of 0.251 cubic kilometers (0.060 cu mi). While there is no public bus service directly to the dam, it can be reached via a route from Aundha Nagnath through Golegaon, Matha, Dhar, and Rupur Camp, with private transportation necessary from Dharphata, located 8 kilometers away. The proposed Light Interferometer Gravitational Observatory (LIGO-India) site is situated approximately 6 kilometers from the dam. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Bhatagaon" class="section">
            <h2>Bhatagaon</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Bhatagaon" class="section-image">
            <p>Parbhani is a prominent city in the Marathwada region of Maharashtra, India, serving as the administrative headquarters for the district bearing the same name. Located approximately 200 kilometers from Aurangabad, the regional headquarters, and 491 kilometers from the state capital Mumbai, Parbhani is well-connected to other significant cities of Maharashtra and neighboring states like Telangana via road and rail networks. The city and surrounding district are heavily influenced by the Deccan lava flows, forming the foundation of its fertile soil, rich in nutrients, situated within the Godavari Valley. The economy of Parbhani is predominantly agricultural, with major crops including Jowar, Bajra, Wheat, Cotton, and various oilseeds. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Wadgaon Dam" class="section">
            <h2>Wadgaon Dam</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Wadgaon Dam" class="section-image">
            <p>The Wadgaon Dam, constructed in 1997, is an earthen dam with a concrete gated spillway built on the Wunna River, located in Wadgaon village within the Umrer Taluka of Nagpur district, Maharashtra. It serves primarily for irrigation and providing water to the Butibori Industrial Area (MIDC), supplying industrial and domestic water as well as irrigation water for a substantial gross command area. The dam is a considerable structure, measuring 23.65 meters in maximum height and 5370 meters in length, with a gross storage capacity of 152.60 Million Cubic Meters (MCM) and a live storage capacity of 136 MCM. It is important to note that the Wadgaon Dam, also referred to as Lower Wunna (Nand) Dam, is part of the Lower Wunna Project along with the Nand Dam, which together irrigate land in both Nagpur and Wardha districts. While the dam is situated near Nagpur, some sources mistakenly associate it with Parbhani district, which instead contains the Ambeohal Dam. There is also a village called Wadgaon Sukre in Parbhani, according to GeoIQ. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

